25|$|Khudekov's {{libretto}} for La <b>Bayadère</b> (meaning The Temple Dancer or The Temple Maiden) {{tells the}} story of the <b>bayadère</b> Nikiya and the warrior Solor, who have sworn eternal fidelity to one another. The High Brahmin, however, is also in love with Nikiya and learns of her relationship with Solor. Moreover, the Rajah Dugmanta of Golconda has selected Solor to wed his daughter Gamzatti (or Hamsatti, as she is known in the original production), and Nikiya, unaware of this arrangement, agrees to dance at the couple's betrothal celebrations.|$|E
